<h2 id="where-you-should-be-at">Where you should be at</h2>
<p>You should all have created your own blog by now - if not the following is a quick sum-up of what we did to set it up:</p>

<ol class="task-list">
  <li class="task-list-item"><input type="checkbox" class="task-list-item-checkbox" disabled="disabled" checked="checked" />Fork https://github.com/barryclark/jekyll-now</li>
  <li class="task-list-item"><input type="checkbox" class="task-list-item-checkbox" disabled="disabled" checked="checked" />Rename the forked repo to yourusername.github.io (or yourusername.github.io/repositoryname)</li>
  <li class="task-list-item"><input type="checkbox" class="task-list-item-checkbox" disabled="disabled" />Clone the forked repo in your machine</li>
  <li class="task-list-item"><input type="checkbox" class="task-list-item-checkbox" disabled="disabled" checked="checked" />Head to yourusername.github.io (or yourusername.github.io/repositoryname) and check what it looks like out-of-the-box</li>
  <li class="task-list-item"><input type="checkbox" class="task-list-item-checkbox" disabled="disabled" checked="checked" />Edit the _config.yml file with your info (blog title, description, social media, etc.)</li>
  <li class="task-list-item"><input type="checkbox" class="task-list-item-checkbox" disabled="disabled" />Create your first post</li>
</ol>

<p>As you can see, I havenâ€™t ticked 3. since you havenâ€™t seen that yet, but itâ€™s good practice to work locally and use Git to sync your local repo with your remote repo (in your case, GitHub (Pages)).</p>

